You'll remember from our last show that a First Contact story is one which humans and

00:12.240 --> 00:13.640
aliens meet for the first time.

00:14.380 --> 00:18.080
Our treatment of the topic this time will emphasize movies dealing with the First Contact

01:18.240 --> 01:21.440
The 40s and 50s would be a classic period for the Bug-Eyed Monster movie.

01:21.960 --> 01:23.680
Recall some of the titles of those years.

01:24.760 --> 01:26.480
It came from outer space.

01:27.200 --> 01:27.700
The blob.

01:28.680 --> 01:29.120
Them.

01:30.020 --> 01:30.480
The thing.

01:31.620 --> 01:35.140
I remember a lot of those movies too, particularly it came from outer space, were in 3D.

01:36.200 --> 01:39.860
And of course that was even more horrifying when your Bug-Eyed Monster would be in three

01:39.860 --> 01:40.900
dimensions rather than two.

01:41.340 --> 01:46.200
And of course everyone had to wear the glasses, the special 3D glasses to appreciate the effects.

01:47.560 --> 01:50.940
But of course those movies were almost all the same.

01:51.100 --> 01:56.740
They all tried to outdo each other in the weirdness of their Bug-Eyed Monsters.

01:59.200 --> 02:01.460
The hostility that they would have toward humans.

02:02.540 --> 02:04.180
Destructive power that they each had.

02:04.680 --> 02:06.320
Today would seem a little ridiculous to us.

02:06.480 --> 02:09.040
Of course there are some movies today which we can talk about a little bit later which

02:09.040 --> 02:13.020
go back to that early trend of the Bug-Eyed Monsters.

02:13.500 --> 02:17.060
I think one of the reasons for that might be the time period in which they were made.

02:17.240 --> 02:23.560
Being in the 40s and the 50s, the era of World War II, shortly after World War II, entering

02:23.560 --> 02:25.780
into McCarthyism and the Cold War.

02:26.920 --> 02:33.180
Anything that wasn't one of us must be one of them and couldn't possibly be friendly.

02:34.640 --> 02:42.400
And that probably led to a lot of the, it came from outer space type of movie.

02:42.960 --> 02:45.500
Of course that has a long tradition behind it, the monster.

02:45.860 --> 02:50.660
Back to the very beginnings of literature, human literature, the Sumerian Epic of Gilgamesh,

02:50.780 --> 02:54.940
the Greek epics of Homer, the Cyclops, the One Eyed Creatures.

02:56.460 --> 03:02.140
All the ancient heroes had to face some kind of monster, some kind of alien creature.

03:03.120 --> 03:05.980
You can trace that through all periods of literary history, all cultures.

03:06.800 --> 03:09.100
And of course for science fiction that was perfect.

03:10.040 --> 03:13.480
They could pick up on that, they could have their Bug-Eyed Monsters arrive in space vehicles.

03:14.400 --> 03:16.880
They could do anything they wanted to in making them weird.

03:17.280 --> 03:20.860
It was just another vehicle for the larger than life hero in the...

03:20.860 --> 03:21.780
Right, a formula story.

03:21.900 --> 03:22.980
Out of this world monster.

03:23.220 --> 03:24.240
A formula story, exactly.

03:24.240 --> 03:28.160
And of course all those Bug-Eyed Monster movies would have a beautiful heroine.

03:28.400 --> 03:33.820
Of course with not many clothes on, of course the monster usually wanted her for some reason.

03:34.460 --> 03:36.100
And the hero had to rescue her.

03:36.660 --> 03:38.520
And it was a typical formula story.

03:39.460 --> 03:44.420
One of the first breaks in those formula stories was Robert Wise's The Day the Earth

03:44.420 --> 03:45.080
Stood Still.

03:46.420 --> 03:50.620
And this was made in 1951 and it was...

03:50.620 --> 04:00.520
The premise behind the story was an advanced being and his companion land on the earth,

04:01.380 --> 04:03.400
make initial contact with the earthlings.

04:03.780 --> 04:07.220
And the earthlings first contact with them is violent.

04:07.540 --> 04:08.760
They shoot him on the spot.

04:10.080 --> 04:18.460
And his message is that if the earth doesn't shape up and get their internal conflicts

04:18.460 --> 04:22.240
under control they will not be allowed to take them off planet.

04:24.920 --> 04:28.740
And he is in essence a benevolent alien.

04:30.380 --> 04:33.880
And this was a new sort of trend for science fiction movies.

04:34.000 --> 04:36.040
This hadn't really been expounded on before.

04:36.580 --> 04:37.760
Especially at that time.

04:37.860 --> 04:39.420
That wasn't long after the Second World War.

04:39.660 --> 04:42.080
No one is right there on the mill with McCarthyism period.

04:42.700 --> 04:43.120
Right.

04:43.420 --> 04:47.400
You recall that story by Leinster where he equates the aliens with the Japanese, you

04:47.400 --> 04:48.240
know the vicious enemy.

04:48.540 --> 04:53.860
To have a movie like this in the, what was it, the 51 where the alien is friendly and

04:53.860 --> 04:58.680
non-aggressive and the humans he comes in contact with wish to destroy him.

04:59.280 --> 05:02.980
That must have been a great change for theater goers to run across that kind of science fiction

05:02.980 --> 05:03.280
movie.

05:03.600 --> 05:04.960
And it was extremely popular.

05:05.740 --> 05:06.920
Wasn't there a robot in that movie?

05:07.040 --> 05:08.600
Wasn't his companion, you mentioned his companion.

05:08.700 --> 05:10.220
Wasn't the companion a robot or a?

05:10.700 --> 05:19.360
Yes, in the movie Clatu the quote human alien had a companion robot named Gort.

05:20.060 --> 05:26.460
Now in the short story this is taken from farewell to the master.

05:27.560 --> 05:34.460
It ends up that the master is really the robot and the companion is the human.

05:34.460 --> 05:38.460
But this is never really brought out in the movie version of it.

05:39.680 --> 05:43.500
Gort in the movie is a sort of inner planetary policeman.

05:45.120 --> 05:50.340
Of course in a way the day the Earth stood still was tied to its time period.

05:51.440 --> 05:59.740
The war was over and treaties had been signed and this might have been a way of expressing

05:59.740 --> 06:03.440
the brotherhood of man.

06:03.620 --> 06:05.640
The fact that we had gone through a huge war.

06:06.220 --> 06:08.220
We killed other human beings, other living creatures.

06:08.920 --> 06:13.780
And the movie did not, I don't think it presented humans in a very fine way.

06:13.800 --> 06:18.260
We could see ourselves as war makers, as aggressors, as having gone through a terrible war.

06:18.560 --> 06:20.240
Perhaps that movie had a message to it.

06:20.400 --> 06:23.080
Making us see ourselves is a great country.

06:23.080 --> 06:24.300
I believe it did.

06:24.920 --> 06:33.600
It used a common formula for movies of that time in which the military were the war makers

06:33.600 --> 06:42.300
and the scientists were sort of the intellectual far-seeing peacemakers.

06:42.840 --> 06:46.600
And that was brought out at the end of the movie where the collection of scientists gathered

06:46.600 --> 06:52.920
and they wanted to speak with Clatu and the military were saying, well no this is now

06:52.920 --> 06:55.600
dangerous and it's now a military operation.

06:55.820 --> 07:00.740
And then Clatu comes out and gives his final and rather famous speech and then they depart.

07:02.040 --> 07:06.680
Another movie which treated the aliens more sensitively I think was also in the 1950s,

07:07.180 --> 07:09.080
1955, This Island Earth.

07:10.460 --> 07:17.920
This Island Earth, the crux of that story was there was a planet farthest apart of our

07:17.920 --> 07:26.020
galaxy which was at war with a totally alien race and they had come to Earth to use some

07:26.020 --> 07:33.160
of the Earth people's technology plus their expertise and just the manpower to build some

07:33.160 --> 07:39.880
more weapons and then transport them back to Madaluna which was the planet which they

07:39.880 --> 07:40.400
came from.

07:40.780 --> 07:45.060
There are a highly intelligent race which used several subsystems of the race on their

07:45.060 --> 07:54.460
planet, one of them being a rather insect-like monster which provided one of the more harrowing

07:54.460 --> 07:59.420
moments in the movie where the monster gets loose on board the ship and of course chases

07:59.420 --> 08:02.020
the harrowing around the ship before it's eventually destroyed.

08:04.700 --> 08:08.880
It treated the aliens as a benevolent creature in the end.

08:10.100 --> 08:15.980
The alien who transported them to Madaluna takes them back to Earth and leaves them there before

08:15.980 --> 08:21.060
his ship eventually runs out of fuel and burns up in the atmosphere.

08:22.980 --> 08:27.680
But at the same time even in the 50s you would have, in fact you always have this, a return

08:27.680 --> 08:28.920
to the bug-eyed monster motif.

08:29.680 --> 08:33.440
The first version of the invasion of the body snatchers was in 1956.

08:34.880 --> 08:36.960
Of course we've had another version recently.

08:37.260 --> 08:40.220
Yes, it was remade in 1979.

08:40.740 --> 08:43.060
But that is totally a scare movie.

08:43.820 --> 08:47.640
Not only are you meeting aliens but their particular form.

08:48.460 --> 08:50.880
In fact they're not intelligent aliens if I recall correctly.

08:50.980 --> 08:53.700
They simply take over the host body in a habit.

08:53.780 --> 08:58.960
They take over the host body and they overlay the host with their own emotions.

08:59.980 --> 09:01.100
Their own motivations.

09:01.200 --> 09:02.280
Well really their own motivations.

09:02.440 --> 09:04.360
They're not really very emotional creatures.

09:07.000 --> 09:11.040
They're very unemotional, very logical.

09:11.920 --> 09:15.200
You don't get very good grasp of what the aliens are like at all.

09:15.320 --> 09:24.080
The aliens are a spore-like creature which is a parasitic and it literally reconstructs

09:24.080 --> 09:32.460
a new human from the original human's tissue and finally absorbs it into its own system

09:32.460 --> 09:38.420
and kills the original human and the duplicate human comes alive with all the memories of

09:38.420 --> 09:42.680
the original human but in sort of a new order, new pattern.

09:43.260 --> 09:44.840
And of course they are here to conquer.

09:45.080 --> 09:46.940
They are here to take over the earth.

09:47.480 --> 09:52.340
Even if it isn't an intelligent conflict, why, that is the kind of thing that they are

09:52.340 --> 09:52.940
built to do.

09:53.320 --> 10:00.120
This is taken from an old theory by Arrhenius that life on earth started from spores which

10:00.120 --> 10:04.460
migrated through space on the wings of the solar wind perhaps, landed on earth and then

10:04.460 --> 10:05.460
began life here.

10:05.600 --> 10:07.980
It's an interesting theory, discredited but still interesting.

10:08.220 --> 10:11.200
Well the second version of the movie, the recent one, I think it's two years old or

10:11.200 --> 10:16.380
so, the beginning of that I think in a lot of ways the earlier version was the better,

10:16.500 --> 10:16.960
the classic.

10:17.320 --> 10:22.340
But the beginning of the second one was well done showing the spores traveling through

10:22.340 --> 10:26.340
space, arriving on earth and becoming part of our ecology and eventually taking over

10:26.340 --> 10:26.860
human bodies.

10:28.680 --> 10:30.380
But that's a true horror movie.

10:30.980 --> 10:37.760
You know not only are we up against aliens but when you think of some non-human creature

10:37.760 --> 10:42.760
taking over your body or destroying your existence but using your physical structure where you

10:42.760 --> 10:46.780
have no control, that's, you can see where people would be horrified at such a thing.

10:47.160 --> 10:50.980
In most first context stories at least you have some kind of alien with a personality

10:51.500 --> 10:54.820
hostile or non-hostile, you can talk with them but here you haven't got anything you

10:54.820 --> 10:56.880
can really talk to or argue with.

10:58.840 --> 11:03.080
Now the aliens are really humans who have changed their mind.

11:04.360 --> 11:06.500
That's really the only way you could look at them in the movie.

11:07.220 --> 11:15.720
It's an alien being in the movie was somebody who you once knew but suddenly their system

11:15.720 --> 11:23.120
of values and what they held dear to them they have just simply changed their mind and

11:23.120 --> 11:24.440
become a different person.

11:25.720 --> 11:28.360
2001 I think could be called the first contact movie.

11:29.120 --> 11:36.080
It's a very different type, again you have no aliens in it but it is an excellent first

11:36.080 --> 11:41.920
course based on Clark's short story The Sentinel and along with Kubrick he collaborated on

11:41.920 --> 11:47.940
the movie and it probably is, most people consider it to be the best science fiction

11:47.940 --> 11:52.280
movie I ever made, obviously a matter of opinion.

11:54.420 --> 12:01.520
But of course similar also to his book Childhoods End in which the alien, even though we never

12:01.520 --> 12:05.080
meet the aliens and don't know much about them they are clearly superior to human beings.

12:05.240 --> 12:09.720
In fact they have come in and taken a guiding hand in the development of the human species.

12:09.980 --> 12:13.680
Yes, they have actually, yes, you get the impression at the first of the movie that

12:13.680 --> 12:15.600
they had been responsible for evolution.

12:17.200 --> 12:21.380
Taking an ape-like or man-like creature was still seemingly an ape and guiding it along

12:21.380 --> 12:26.960
evolutionary paths until they reached the point they can travel to the moon and find

12:26.960 --> 12:35.320
the next signal in the terms of this huge monolith and it emitted some high, some signal,

12:35.500 --> 12:40.740
some frequency that they could follow and they sent, of course they sent their huge ship

12:41.500 --> 12:44.280
following that signal with Hal, a computer in control of it.

12:44.960 --> 12:49.740
And at the end of the movie of course the star child, very ambiguous ending but still

12:49.740 --> 12:51.020
at the same time it was optimistic.

12:51.640 --> 12:57.140
You get the idea of a new stage in human evolution just as the ape-like creatures had become

12:57.140 --> 13:03.700
men at the beginning because of the alien's help that humans in the movie were ready to

13:03.700 --> 13:09.280
move on to some further stage in evolution, some higher level because of the help of the

13:09.280 --> 13:09.660
aliens.

13:10.180 --> 13:16.120
And I think this is about the only way that you can depict an alien who is very far above

13:16.120 --> 13:21.260
you. You can't really, we can't do it because we're limited in our human imaginations and

13:21.260 --> 13:24.820
you almost have to depict him sort of off stage meddling in human affairs.

13:25.060 --> 13:28.780
And many times in the movies they have to depict him off stage because special effects

13:28.780 --> 13:29.820
couldn't accommodate him.

13:30.080 --> 13:30.720
That's true too.

13:31.300 --> 13:34.660
Well with that particular movie of course there was no problem with the special effects

13:34.660 --> 13:41.940
on the alien. All they had to do was to conceive of this monolithic signal, this monolith I

13:41.940 --> 13:42.440
guess of what you call it.

13:42.460 --> 13:48.800
Some sort of transponder or you never really were given a concrete definition as to what

13:48.800 --> 13:55.120
it was other than it was something that Signal D'Arre brought about, Jump and Man's intellect

13:55.120 --> 13:56.400
or his reasoning.

13:57.140 --> 14:02.360
It's interesting to read the story, the Sentinel from which the movie came. There's a very

14:02.360 --> 14:09.680
great difference. In the story an expedition to the moon comes upon a monolith. It's on

14:09.680 --> 14:12.440
the surface by the way, in the movie it was buried, they had to dig it out.

14:13.080 --> 14:18.100
But in the story it was on the surface and of course it stuck out to such an extent that

14:18.100 --> 14:19.080
the humans couldn't miss it.

14:19.940 --> 14:24.280
And they go up and they study it, they realize it's the product of a far superior culture.

14:25.320 --> 14:31.440
They also can calculate that it's been millions of years since the monolith was set up on

14:31.440 --> 14:36.800
the moon. They don't know what the purpose of it is. But of course the point of the story

14:36.800 --> 14:40.880
is wondering, who were they, when did they come, why did they come, where are they now.

14:41.700 --> 14:46.880
And Clark leads us to believe at the end of it that the aliens, whoever they were, set

14:46.880 --> 14:53.260
this up on the moon to signal them as to when the humans had reached a sufficient point

14:53.260 --> 14:55.920
in technology that they could reach the moon from Earth.

14:57.420 --> 15:01.420
And of course the movie created one of the greatest or most memorable characters if you

15:01.420 --> 15:07.280
can call him that in science fiction environment and that of course is Hal, the computer. That

15:07.280 --> 15:10.560
was well done I thought. He becomes a character in his own right.

15:25.120 --> 15:29.840
Consider the television audience. You have to have something that's familiar, you have

15:29.840 --> 15:34.920
to have something that's sharp. If you had a show that showed aliens as benevolent or

15:34.920 --> 15:38.900
dealt with any kinds of deep questions regarding first contact, I don't think it would work.

15:38.900 --> 15:43.060
You have to go back to the bug-eyed monster, the menace, something that people can feel

15:43.060 --> 15:49.760
quickly and understand quickly. You can't get as much depth in a movie as you can in

15:49.760 --> 15:55.600
a book and you can get even less depth in a TV show. You have to stick to action. Even

15:55.600 --> 16:00.500
Star Trek for example, although it did look at a lot of different interesting themes and

16:00.940 --> 16:05.500
work on some controversial subjects, was essentially as Roddenberry admitted, a wagon train to the

16:05.500 --> 16:06.900
stars. It was an adventure series.

16:07.420 --> 16:12.380
There were a number of Star Trek episodes which dealt with first contact. One of them

16:12.380 --> 16:14.420
I think based on a Frederick Brown short story, Arena.

16:17.220 --> 16:27.080
Yeah, that one being where the enterprise encountered an aggressive alien force on one

16:27.080 --> 16:35.340
of our Federation planets and drove them off planet and then continued to pursue them across

16:35.500 --> 16:46.900
the galaxy and were stopped by extremely vastly superior race and one person from each crew

16:46.900 --> 16:53.840
on each ship was taken down to fight in this arena on this world. One being the Gorn,

16:54.660 --> 17:00.380
a lizard-like creature and the other being Captain Kirk. They eventually had a rather

17:00.380 --> 17:05.800
long and arduous battle at which Kirk was eventually victorious. He decided not to kill

17:05.800 --> 17:13.020
the Gorn which proved our superiority and our humanity over the Gorn race and we were

17:13.020 --> 17:22.840
spared annihilation because the superior race which was hosting this battle had decided

17:22.840 --> 17:29.180
to kill the victor because they would be the most dangerous, but instead they had spared

17:29.180 --> 17:33.440
both the Gorn and the human race and allowed them to live on.

17:35.140 --> 17:42.860
That's almost an obvious way of treating the first contact material in that you have an

17:42.860 --> 17:47.880
alien who looks like a reptile, who is a reptile. You have a human being and they are going

17:47.880 --> 17:54.640
at one-on-one combat with the loser to lose everything his ship, his crew and so forth.

17:55.600 --> 18:02.020
That isn't a motif in many ancient literatures, in fact in the Greek epics, in the Iliad,

18:02.520 --> 18:08.140
the prototype of war stories. Various times in the battle, one of the Greek warriors,

18:08.300 --> 18:13.500
one of the Trojan warriors would step out into an arena, the battlefield, everybody

18:13.500 --> 18:18.120
else would gather around and they would go at it one-on-one. The rules being the winner

18:18.120 --> 18:20.320
would take all, the loser would of course lose all.

18:20.780 --> 18:25.060
That seems to be fairly common in a lot of cultures, that was fairly common in the Indian

18:25.060 --> 18:30.360
cultures in the Northern United States and down in New Mexico and South America. It's

18:30.360 --> 18:34.360
also fairly common in African cultures, so this seems to be a world-

18:34.360 --> 18:40.720
Easily translatable into the alien first contact material, very dramatic, very visual, and I

18:40.720 --> 18:44.220
thought that was one of their better episodes. That's one thing television can do, it does

18:44.220 --> 18:48.200
have limitations, but it's very dramatic, it's very visual, it's very immediate, and

18:48.200 --> 18:52.280
they have that kind of contact. Of course with the message at the end of it, when the

18:52.280 --> 18:56.200
human did not kill the alien, the idea that non-aggression got him something.

18:57.240 --> 19:01.240
A couple of times Star Trek did manage to bring across a first contact story that was

19:01.240 --> 19:07.120
not immediate action oriented. The story of the Hortov, of course, is one of their best

19:07.120 --> 19:13.920
ones. An alien being was apparently killing off a colony on some planet and it turned out

19:13.920 --> 19:19.400
that this alien being was the last survivor of an almost dead race who was protecting

19:19.400 --> 19:24.280
her young. They didn't recognize, the humans did not recognize this because the young and

19:24.280 --> 19:30.500
the alien herself looked like pieces of rock, pieces of mineral, but it turned out that

19:31.200 --> 19:36.260
she was merely exhibiting mother love. This is kind of a difficult thing to portray on

19:36.260 --> 19:40.160
television, and I think it was to Star Trek's credit they were able to bring it off successfully.

19:41.800 --> 19:46.160
I think one of the best things television has done as long as we're talking about television in regard to

19:46.160 --> 19:50.940
first contact stories is one that I don't often think of as first contact, but I believe it. It should be

19:50.940 --> 19:56.820
considered as such, and that would be Ray Bradbury's Martian Chronicles. I think of all the first

19:56.820 --> 20:02.880
contact works I can think of. Perhaps this better than any other illustrates the learning of something

20:02.880 --> 20:09.380
about ourselves, a reflection of our own culture because of the contact. Of course all we do, we go to

20:09.380 --> 20:18.520
Mars and contact the remnants of a much, much older Martian culture, and because of that contact we see

20:18.520 --> 20:25.420
ourselves as hostile, as aggressive. Of course this is a series of short stories, you know, over a

20:25.420 --> 20:32.300
period of time. We see ourselves as materialistic, you know, all of the bad qualities which the

20:32.300 --> 20:40.240
human race does have. And of course finally the humans that are on Mars are locked there because of the fact

20:40.240 --> 20:47.780
Earth destroys itself, which they can tell, but I believe that was a three-part episode on television. I think

20:47.780 --> 20:54.420
one of the better things they've done on television, but it was excellent first contact material.

