written by Dan O'Bannon and others. It is essentially a something-goes-bump-in-the-night horror movie in that the

21:29.300 --> 21:36.820
Earthlings are traveling along in a gigantic mining ship and they're awakened by their computers and told that

21:36.820 --> 21:43.920
some sort of signal has been picked up emanating from this planet and they go down to investigate and a rather

21:43.920 --> 21:58.260
gruesome, very non-benevolent alien is brought on board and the alien systematically starts dispatching the crew and also

21:58.260 --> 22:07.840
using the crew as a part of its reproductive cycle. It implants egg inside them and the egg eventually forms a pod and the

22:07.840 --> 22:15.740
pod sits around waiting for some other life form to come by and when the other life form comes by it implants itself inside it and

22:15.740 --> 22:27.920
then furthers implants an egg inside that life form, in this case being a human life form, and the egg matures further and then uses the

22:27.920 --> 22:36.560
life form as food and then breaks out of them and then grows into the adult alien which goes around searching for more life forms

22:36.560 --> 22:48.080
to implant eggs and so on and so on. The thing about this movie which brought it out of the mediocre was its stunning visuals.

22:48.920 --> 22:57.720
It was beautifully photographed and the creature that they devised in this is probably one of the best monsters ever created for the screen.

22:59.000 --> 23:02.220
But on the other hand it's still a bug-eyed monster.

23:02.720 --> 23:03.040
Very true.

23:03.180 --> 23:13.600
The movie you're right, the movie was a fine movie and it was saved by the technology, the visual effects, but as some critics remarked and I totally agree with this, it was really a

23:13.600 --> 23:15.400
jaws set in outer space.

23:15.760 --> 23:20.500
Very true. It was a cross between jaws and star wars.

23:22.300 --> 23:32.240
But still I would say as you mentioned earlier it was an extreme. I mean there are extremes in the treatment of aliens in the movies today and that of course would be the extreme that goes back to the bug-eyed

23:32.240 --> 23:32.880
monster days.

23:33.640 --> 23:41.180
And one of the more optimistic movies that has to deal with first contact is of course Close Encounters of the Third Kind.

24:22.540 --> 24:29.860
That being a movie by Steven Spielberg, written by Steven Spielberg and directed by him also.

24:31.480 --> 24:38.240
I think that probably would be considered the classic first encounter movie in Hollywood history.

24:38.440 --> 24:49.380
It incorporates a lot of the elements of first contact that UFO specialists and others interested in first contact on a real basis have been talking about for a number of years.

24:49.380 --> 25:12.720
Yes, it was obviously crafted with a lot of love and attention to detail and it seems to me to be a very passionate work and that he obviously wanted to portray and show something that he held very close to himself.

25:13.260 --> 25:22.880
Well consider what it would be like. To me the movie more than anything else, the details of it, the plot structure, all of this was subservient to one thing and that was the feeling.

25:24.140 --> 25:32.220
What's it going to be like when we actually and truly make first contact with an alien culture? What are we going to feel like?

25:32.940 --> 25:37.740
Now of course one way that the early movies treated that was well they're going to be monsters, they're going to be hostile.

25:38.020 --> 25:40.820
We can't show them where we live if it happens off the earth.

25:41.300 --> 25:51.320
But this movie at the end of it in particular you got a sense of wonder, a sense of fascination, a sense of awe that we have contacted an alien culture.

25:51.880 --> 25:55.040
They are not hostile. What's it going to mean?

25:55.180 --> 25:58.400
It's an opportunity for us rather than something we should be afraid of.

25:58.740 --> 26:01.320
Yes, it's an extremely optimistic ending to the movie.

26:02.220 --> 26:10.780
Now of course the communication in the movie was, if you can call it that I suppose, was sonics or sound or tonal qualities rather than any kind of language or...

26:10.780 --> 26:12.660
Yes they communicated with sound and light.

26:15.700 --> 26:19.140
And the movie is actually done on two levels.

26:19.260 --> 26:31.300
One with the electrical technician working for the power company who had an encounter with an alien craft which transferred this image of where the alien culture was.

26:31.320 --> 26:32.580
And where they were going to land to him.

26:32.760 --> 26:40.660
On the second level it was an international organization which was tracking down possible landing sites.

26:41.480 --> 26:47.420
And using extreme advanced technology was determining where they were going to land, when they were going to land.

26:47.500 --> 26:48.960
They had this all figured out in advance.

26:50.080 --> 26:59.800
And when they finally, or hero convert, finally gets to the area where the craft is going to land.

26:59.800 --> 27:13.460
All these other people from all over the world have also converged on this one spot because they have also had sightings and they've also had this thought implanted in them that something is going to happen here of extreme importance.

27:13.660 --> 27:16.340
So they've all going there to find out what it is.

27:17.080 --> 27:29.000
And once first contact is made and the aliens are actually seen and our people go on board to a journey with them on through space.

27:29.000 --> 27:33.440
The movie ends on just a very, very high note, very, very high optimism.

27:34.240 --> 27:50.220
I think that scene where the principal alien ship lands and the people have prepared for them with the sound and the lights and the interchange, the sound, at first very tentative, sort of timid.

27:50.380 --> 27:52.040
And finally it works up to a huge crescendo.

27:52.040 --> 28:00.560
The looks on the faces of the humans as they realize what they've done here is just, to me, is one of the most beautiful things done in science fiction movies.

28:00.780 --> 28:12.540
Even the military personnel, and you traditionally in the movies see the military as fairly hard people and not willing to go along with this kind of viewpoint, but everybody there is staring up at the mothership in awe and wonder.

28:13.020 --> 28:14.100
It's quite a great feeling.

28:14.100 --> 28:18.360
I can't think of a movie that would be more extreme from Alien than this one.

28:18.740 --> 28:21.200
It's almost totally different at the other end of the spectrum.

28:22.220 --> 28:28.040
You know, the aliens are non-aggressive, they are friendly, they are superior, but they do seem to be benevolent too.

28:38.600 --> 28:39.640
This is Daryl Lane.

28:39.920 --> 28:40.560
Keith Johnson.

28:40.780 --> 28:41.360
And David Carson.

